#let images = (
  "24.1": (
    caption: [Virtually every part of the plant is adapted to coexist with the organisms in its immediate environment. The diagram shows various organisms interacting with different plant parts: leaf herbivores, pollinators, ants, leaf parasites on aerial parts; competitors, symbionts, root herbivores, soil microbes, nematodes, and root pathogens in the soil environment.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.2": (
    caption: [Model for Nod factor signaling in the root epidermis during symbiotic nitrogen fixation. The pathway shows receptor kinases (NFR1 and NFR5) binding Nod factors, initiating a signaling cascade involving nuclear calcium oscillations, activation of transcription factors (NSP1, NSP2, NIN), and expression of symbiotic genes leading to nodule formation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.3": (
    caption: [Oscillations in the Ca²⁺ concentration in an emerging root hair of Medicago truncatula responding to the addition of Nod factor. The plant has been engineered to express a calcium-sensitive fluorescent protein that allows visualization of calcium concentration changes over time, showing characteristic periodic spikes in nuclear calcium levels.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.4": (
    caption: [Diagram of the interactions between plants and plant growth-promoting rhizobacteria, such as Pseudomonas aeruginosa. These bacteria release antibiotics and volatile compounds that promote plant growth, increase nutrient availability, and provide protection against pathogens through induced systemic resistance.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.5": (
    caption: [Examples of mechanical barriers developed by plants for defense. (A) Thorns on a lemon tree (Citrus sp.) are modified branches. (B) Spines on a cactus are modified leaves. (C) Prickles on a rose stem are epidermal outgrowths. (D) Trichomes (plant hairs) on various plant surfaces provide physical barriers against herbivores.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.6": (
    caption: [Trichomes of nettles (Urtica dioica) have a multicellular base with a single stinging cell protruding. The cell wall of this single cell is reinforced with silica at the tip, forming a sharp point. When touched, the tip breaks off, and the cell injects a mixture of histamine, acetylcholine, and other chemicals into the skin of the animal, causing a painful burning sensation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.7": (
    caption: [Calcium oxalate crystals (raphides) from the leaf of an agave (Agave weberi). These raphides are tightly packed in specialized cells called idioblasts. When tissue is damaged, the sharp needle-like crystals are released and can penetrate the mouth and digestive tract of herbivores, causing pain and deterring feeding.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.8": (
    caption: [Leaves of the sensitive plant (Mimosa pudica) respond rapidly to touch by folding in their individual leaflets within seconds. This rapid movement is caused by changes in turgor pressure in specialized motor cells at the base of each leaflet. The movement may startle herbivores or reduce the apparent leaf area available for feeding.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.9": (
    caption: [Specialized metabolites are located at the interface between primary metabolism and the interaction of organisms with their environment. The diagram shows how primary metabolic pathways (amino acid metabolism, shikimate pathway, and acetyl-CoA/malonyl-CoA pathways) branch to produce specialized metabolites including alkaloids, phenylpropanoids, terpenoids, and other defensive compounds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.10": (
    caption: [Constitutive chemical defenses are effective against many different herbivores, including insects and mammals. Examples include hemlock (Cicuta sp.) which produces cicutoxin, a diacetylene that prolongs the repolarization of neuronal action potentials, and foxglove (Digitalis sp.) which produces digitoxin, a cardiac glycoside that inhibits ATPase activity and can increase myocardial contraction.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.11": (
    caption: [Resin stored in its resin ducts is released when herbivores damage the plant. (A) Resin duct in the wood of a conifer (Araucaria sp.), showing the duct surrounded by secretory cells that release resin components. (B) When the duct is damaged, resin flows out and can trap insects or seal wounds. The resin contains terpenoids, resin acids, and other toxic compounds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.12": (
    caption: [Laticifers are made of individual cells and can occur either as articulated systems (single cells connected by small tubes) or non-articulated systems (one large syncytial cell). Latex in the laticifers is released when the plant is damaged, containing toxic specialized metabolites, proteins, and rubber that can deter herbivores or seal wounds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.13": (
    caption: [While most herbivores are very susceptible to the toxic metabolites in the latex of milkweed and oleander plants, some insect herbivores incorporate these compounds (cardiac glycosides) into their bodies and show this to potential predators by presenting bright warning colors. Examples include monarch butterfly caterpillars and the milkweed aphid (Aphis nerii).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.14": (
    caption: [In members of the Poaceae family, benzoxazinoids are major defensive specialized metabolites derived from the tryptophan pathway. The compounds DIBOA (2,4-dihydroxy-1,4-benzoxazin-3-one) and DIMBOA (2,4-dihydroxy-7-methoxy-1,4-benzoxazin-3-one) are stored in the vacuole as glycosides coupled to glucose. After tissue damage, the glycosides are hydrolyzed by enzymes, releasing toxic aglycones that deter herbivores.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.15": (
    caption: [Hydrolysis of glucosinolates into mustardy volatiles. The isothiocyanates and nitriles are noxious products of these reactions. First the sugar is cleaved by the enzymatic action of a thioglucosidase to yield an aglycone product that spontaneously decomposes into volatile toxic products. The example shows sinigrin, a major glucosinolate of black mustard seeds and horseradish roots, where R is CH₂=CH—CH₂–.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.16": (
    caption: [Cyanogenic glycosides break down to produce hydrogen cyanide providing a constitutive chemical defense against herbivores. (A) Enzyme-catalyzed hydrolysis of cyanogenic glycosides releases hydrogen cyanide through a two-step process: glycosidase cleaves the sugar, then the cyanohydrin decomposes spontaneously or via hydroxynitrile lyase. (B) Examples include dhurrin from sorghum, linamarin from cassava, and amygdalin from almond and stone fruit seeds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.17": (
    caption: [Structures of major insect-derived elicitors. (A) Linolenic acid–amino acid conjugates such as volicitin have been found to induce the release of volatile specialized metabolites in maize seedlings. The fatty acid component is derived from ingested plant tissue and conjugated to glutamine in the insect gut. (B) Two classes of caeliferins have been isolated from regurgitant of the grasshopper Schistocerca americana, with sulfated hydroxyl groups that enhance their elicitor activity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.18": (
    caption: [Steps in the pathway for conversion of linolenic acid into jasmonic acid (JA). The first enzymatic steps occur in the chloroplast, producing 12-oxo-phytodienoic acid (OPDA) through the action of lipoxygenase, allene oxide synthase, and allene oxide cyclase. OPDA is then transported to the peroxisome where it is reduced and converted into JA by β-oxidation. Finally, JA is conjugated to isoleucine by the enzyme JAR1 to form the active signaling molecule JA-Ile.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.19": (
    caption: [Jasmonic acid signaling pathway. Jasmonic acid must first be conjugated to isoleucine to form JA-Ile, which then binds to COI1 as part of a SCF^COI1 E3 ubiquitin ligase complex. This complex targets JAZ proteins, which are repressors of transcription. Upon binding, JAZ is ubiquitinated and degraded by the 26S proteasome, releasing transcription factors that activate expression of defense genes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.20": (
    caption: [Systemic response of Arabidopsis to herbivore attack. (A) Injury to the leaf caused by herbivory activates glutamate receptor-like (GLR) ion channels. The GLRs trigger electrical signals that travel through the vascular system alongside waves of chemical signaling including changes in Ca²⁺ concentration and reactive oxygen species (ROS), stimulating jasmonic acid production both locally and in distant tissues. (B) Time course showing the rapid spread of calcium and electrical signals throughout the plant following localized damage.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.21": (
    caption: [Ecological functions of herbivore-induced plant volatiles (HIPV). Many plants release a specific bouquet of volatile organic compounds when attacked by insect herbivores. These volatiles include terpenoids (mono- and sesquiterpenes), alkaloids (indole), phenylpropanoids (methyl salicylate), and green-leaf volatiles. Functions include: (1) attracting natural enemies of herbivores such as parasitic wasps; (2) signaling to neighboring plants to prime their defenses; (3) direct repellence of herbivores; (4) belowground volatile signaling to beneficial nematodes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.22": (
    caption: [Extrafloral nectaries of lima bean (Phaseolus lunatus). These specialized structures secrete nectar on vegetative parts of the plant (not associated with flowers), attracting predatory insects and ants that defend the plant against herbivores.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.23": (
    caption: [Example of circadian rhythms influencing plant defense against herbivory. (A) Trichoplusia ni (cabbage looper) caterpillar feeding on Arabidopsis. (B) Normally the circadian clocks of caterpillars and plants are synchronized, with both caterpillar feeding activity and jasmonate-mediated plant defenses peaking during the day, optimizing plant defenses and reducing caterpillar growth. (C) If the circadian rhythm of Arabidopsis is shifted by 12 hours, the plant's defenses are out of phase with caterpillar feeding, resulting in reduced defense effectiveness and increased caterpillar growth.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.24": (
    caption: [Plant pathogens such as bacteria and fungi have developed various methods for invading plants. Some fungi have mechanisms that allow them to directly penetrate the cuticle and cell wall using appressoria and mechanical pressure. Other fungi and pathogenic bacteria enter through natural openings such as stomata and lenticels, or through existing wounds caused by herbivores or environmental damage.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.25": (
    caption: [Plants have evolved defense responses to multiple danger signals of biotic origin. These include microbe-associated molecular patterns (MAMPs) such as flagellin and chitin, damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs) such as cell wall fragments and extracellular ATP, and pathogen effectors. MAMPs and DAMPs are recognized by pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) on the cell surface, triggering PAMP-triggered immunity (PTI). Effectors are recognized by intracellular NLR proteins, triggering effector-triggered immunity (ETI) which includes the hypersensitive response.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.26": (
    caption: [Toxins and hormones produced by pathogens help pathogens infect plants. Examples include HC-toxin, a cyclic peptide that inhibits histone deacetylase in the nucleus affecting defense gene expression; fusicoccin which binds to and irreversibly activates plasma membrane H⁺-ATPases particularly in stomata; and gibberellins produced by the fungus Gibberella fujikuroi which accelerate plant growth and may promote dispersal of fungal spores.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.27": (
    caption: [Three-dimensional structures of plant resistosomes revealed by cryo-electron microscopy. (A) A TIR-NLR resistosome showing a pathogen effector protein (XopQ, pink) bound to the C-terminus of a TIR-NLR protein (Roq1). Key domains include the C-terminal jelly roll/immunoglobulin-like domain (C-JID, light blue), LRR domain (dark blue), nucleotide-binding domain (NBD, green), and TIR domain (yellow). (B) A CC-NLR resistosome with similar modular architecture but different N-terminal domain structure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.28": (
    caption: [Systemic acquired resistance (SAR) signaling during the response to pathogens. A bacterial infection induces effector-triggered immunity (ETI) and the hypersensitive response, leading to local production of salicylic acid (SA) and N-hydroxy-pipecolic acid (NHP). NHP is conjugated to glucose for systemic transport through the plant. In both local and distal cells, NHP induces expression of defense genes including SA biosynthetic enzymes. SA binds to NPR proteins (NON-EXPRESSOR OF PR GENES) to induce expression of numerous pathogenesis-related (PR) genes, establishing long-lasting immunity throughout the plant.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.29": (
    caption: [Structures of representative phytoalexins found in different plant families. These antimicrobial specialized metabolites are synthesized de novo in response to pathogen attack. Examples include camalexin from Brassicaceae, medicarpin from Fabaceae, and capsidiol from Solanaceae, each with distinct chemical structures but similar defensive functions against a broad spectrum of pathogens.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.30": (
    caption: [Nematode infection of plant roots and formation of specialized feeding structures. Free-living juvenile nematodes are attracted to root secretions. (A) Cyst nematodes (Heterodera and Globodera species) penetrate the root and induce formation of a syncytium in the vasculature by fusing multiple cells. After feeding and reproduction, the female dies forming a protective cyst containing eggs. (B) Root-knot nematodes (Meloidogyne species) induce formation of giant multinucleate cells in the vasculature, resulting in characteristic root galls. The female releases egg masses from which new juveniles hatch.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.31": (
    caption: [Phytotoxic allelopathic compound (±)-catechin produced by spotted knapweed (Centaurea maculosa). This phenolic compound is released from the roots into the soil where it inhibits growth of neighboring plants, giving knapweed a competitive advantage. Catechin causes oxidative stress and affects root development in susceptible species.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.32": (
    caption: [Parasitic plants showing different degrees of dependence on their hosts. (A) Mistletoe (Viscum sp.) growing on a mesquite tree (genus Prosopis) - a hemiparasite that performs some photosynthesis but obtains water and minerals from the host. (B) Green stem of mistletoe penetrating through the bark of the host plant via a haustorium. (C) Dodder (Cuscuta sp.) growing on sand verbenas (Abronia umbellata) - a holoparasite completely dependent on the host for all nutrients. (D) Close-up showing high density of dodder infestation with multiple haustorial connections to the host.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "24.33": (
    caption: [Dodder (Cuscuta sp.) haustorium structure and penetration process. (A) Micrograph showing the haustorium of dodder penetrating the host plant tissues. (B) The disc-like meristem appears in the prehaustorium (green), with epidermally-derived trichome-like elongated cells (yellow) forming attachment to the host surface. (C) The cortex-derived haustorium penetrates deeper into the host tissue. (D) Inside the host, elongated searching hyphae (orange) grow toward the host vasculature. Upon contacting host xylem vessels, they establish a xylem bridge (red) for nutrient uptake.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  )
)
